Description: The latest fabrics, the most advanced technologies, & a remarkably unique R&D process that’s delivers new forms of comfort since 1978.
Headquarters Regions: Greater San Diego Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: STAY WARM We all go outside, no matter what the season. We ski, snowboard, hunt, camp. We walk our dogs, commute to work, watch sports, and even party outside on New Year’s. Whatever gets you out there; you want to stay warm. Well you’ve come to the right place! Our gear is made with extremities in mind; to keep your hands, feet, face, and head warm and protected. And not just warm enough to grit through it. We mean really warm. Like, surprisingly warm.   COMFORT & FOCUS We’d like you to know two things about Seirus Innovation. First: we believe in comfort. We use the latest fabrics, the most advanced technologies, and a remarkably unique R&D process that’s delivered new forms of comfort every year since 1978. We don’t follow industry trends, we follow comfort. We were the first to bring rechargeable heated gloves to market, and we own 19 patents aimed at making your outdoor experience warm and comfortable. Second: we focus on extremities. That’s it! Other companies spread their focus across base layers, jackets, and sometimes tents. The only thing we think about is redefining all-weather comfort for your head, hands, and feet.   DOING THE RIGHT THING We believe in continually improving our processes to be more sustainable for the sake of the environment. Through our adoption of solar power at our office and warehouse, a move to biodegradable materials over plastic bags, and more we have greatly reduced our carbon and waste footprints. As a family business we know we’re all in this together, so we take care for not only the environment, but our employees, our partners, our suppliers, and of course our customers as well. Our Outreach page shows some of the amazing institutions we are proud to collaborate with in this industry, all of whom are working tirelessly to preserve and bring the joy of the outdoors to everybody.   WHERE WE STARTED Our skills at innovating comfort started back in the late 1970s. Co-founders Joe Edwards and Mike Carey, both avid skiers, each invented a new product that made skiing better. After joining forces, they created a unique R&D culture where everyone at the company critiques, tests, and designs products in an ongoing cycle of invention and reinvention. It leads to great products that get better and better.

Description: Colorado Financial Service Corporation was established in the greater Denver area in 2000.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Denver Area, Western US
Full Description: Colorado Financial is a registered securities broker dealer, member FINRA (www.finra.org) and SIPC (www.sipc.org).  In addition, Colorado Financial  is registered as an investment adviser and is licensed to conduct certain insurance business.  Colorado Financial is dedicated to supporting independent financial services professionals and the clients they serve. They aim to be the securities broker dealer with which high quality independent investment banking and other investment professionals choose to associate for conducting their securities businesses.  Colorado Financial provides “user friendly” and professional back office, administrative, registration, compliance and related services that are tailored to each particular situation.  Colorado Financial Service Corporation was established in the greater Denver area in 2000.  Chet Hebert, our chairman and Chief Executive Officer became the sole owner in 2007, through his ownership of Colorado National Corporation.  Mr. Hebert has wide ranging experiences in the securities industry with several firms and has served in capacities as registered representative, advisor, Branch Manager, Chief Compliance Officer, Financial and Operations Principal and President of independent firms.  In addition, Mr. Hebert was elected by his peers to two separate terms on the FINRA District 3 Committee, including a term as Committee Chairman.  Colorado Financial Service Corporation is the second broker-dealer that Mr. Hebert has had an ownership interest.  Originally established as a limited broker-dealer, Mr. Hebert has grown the firm into a full service broker-dealer providing full service brokerage, private placement securities, investment advisory services, investment banking, EB-5 Placement Services and IRS Section 1031 Like-Kind Exchange services.  The firm maintains membership in the Alternative and Direct Investment Securities Association (ADISA), the Investment Program Association (IPA), and The National Due Diligence Alliance (TNDDA).  Colorado Financial has teamed up with service providers who cater to the independent registered representative led by our fully disclosed clearing partner, the First Southwest Company.

Description: Marijuana Policy Project is a U.S-based organization focused solely on ending marijuana prohibition.
Headquarters Regions: Washington DC Metro Area, Southern US
Full Description: Marijuana Policy Project is a U.S-based organization focused solely on ending marijuana prohibition. Its aim is to change federal law to allow states to determine their own marijuana policies without federal interference, as well as to regulate marijuana like alcohol in all 50 states, D.C., and the five territories. Marijuana Policy Project has been responsible for changing most of the state marijuana laws that have been reformed since 2000, including the legalization of marijuana in Colorado in November 2012 and in Alaska in 2014. The organization is composed of three separate organizations that include the main branch that deals with lobbying and ballot initiatives, the tax-deductible educational branch, and a branch that donates to congressional candidates. In addition, Marijuana Policy Project has state committees in the states where it is running ballot initiatives; these state committees are formed and closed every few years. For the three aforementioned core organizations, the annual budgets are usually 3,000,000 U.S. dollars, 2,000,000 U.S. dollars, and 100,000 U.S. dollars, respectively. Marijuana Policy Project typically has approximately 30 employees, two-thirds of whom are based in its headquarters in Washington, D.C. and this includes two full-time lobbyists on Capitol Hill. In addition, the organization usually has lobbyists on retainer in six or seven state capitals. It was founded in 2012.

The company has such arrangement with the Bonelli Publishing library from Italy, which produces comic books in printed form. Major characters from the Bonelli library include Nathan Never, Legs Weaver and Dylan Dog. Digital Publishing The company intends to commercialize its intellectual property through viable media outlets and channels, including the online content space. It intends to aggregate various online comic properties and develop an online comics âportal,' where it can further interact with the comic-creator and -fan communities through content, reference information, community tools and other interactive features. Full Description: PlayMotion! is a company that produces a next generation videogame technology of the same name. Their product applies practical Computer Vision algorithms to the problem of gesture recognition in a wide array of environments, including theme parks, museums, arcades and exergaming. PlayMotion, in essence, allows players to use the wall of the room as a videogame surface, while a a graphics engine and video projector turn your actions into digital shapes and patterns on a large screen. Full Description: The SAILS Group, Inc. (Supported And Independent Living Services) is an international agency committed to the quality of care, supervision and training of adults and children with intellectual and developmental disabilities. When possible, we help these individuals develop skills, earn income, and live an integrated life in their communities. The SAILS Group, Inc. operates three separate for-profit corporations: SAILS Bakersfield, SAILS Los Angeles and SAILS San Diego. The SAILS Group also provides management and administrative services for two nonprofit corporations: Kids First Foundation (U.S.A.) and Kids First Foundation – Colombia. SAILS Group is committed to providing the most collaborative and multi-dimensional array of services in order to meet the needs of the individuals served. We realize these needs change on an on-going basis, with the ultimate goal of placing an individual in the least restrictive environment. Therefore, SAILS offers a wide range of placement and intervention services. SAILS holds a long-standing history of expertise and success in this field. The group currently operates 37 licensed and/or vendored services among all the companies, 17 of which are Adult Residential Facilities, fifteen are Children’s Group Homes, two are in-home behavioral support programs, and three are adult behavioral day programs. With an additional three programs under development, the SAILS Group will reach 40 facilities by 1st Quarter 2016, indicating a steady growth rate of two per year. With almost two decades of practicing knowledge, over 400 current employees and a proven record of success in working with and molding some of the most behaviorally challenging individuals in the state of California, SAILS’ success is ultimately related to its philosophy, values, structure and consistency that is relayed to both the persons served and staff alike.

Description: Dattoli Cancer Center specializes in radiation oncology and offers minimally invasive and non-surgical treatment options.
Headquarters Regions: East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: The Dattoli Cancer Center, founded by Dr. Michael Dattoli The Benefits of Genetic and Genomic Testing At Dattoli Cancer Center, we employ multiple laboratory tests for genomic and genetic makeup that allow us to determine which specific medications and treatments may be most appropriate for each patient. We utilize both the Invitae Genetic Test and the Myriad myRisk® Hereditary Cancer testing. The Myriad test is a 35-gene panel that identifies elevated risk for eight hereditary cancers. There are a host of genetic pathways and mutations that a patient may have (including BRACA 2, BRCA1, HOXB13, ATM, CHEK2, and CDK1), and they can tell us whether or not a patient is likely to respond well to a particular agent. For example, we know that a patient with positive BRCA1 and especially positive BRCA2 gene mutations will most likely have a shorter effective run with the androgen-blocking drugs Xtandi® and Zytiga®. Another lab test analyzing serum is called a “droplet digital PCR assay,” and it can also help us determine which patients will best respond to those chemical agents, Xtandi® and Zytiga®. It should be noted that genetic markers are also important in light of the patient’s family history. We want to know what the family history is with regard to other cancers. We can see that a patient’s daughters may be prone to breast cancer or ovarian cancer; and now even colon and pancreatic cancers enter the picture in the spectrum related to prostate cancer. These cancers are essentially on the same page in our genetic makeup. Melanoma is also now seen to be genetically related to prostate cancer, and all of these cancers may occur at increased frequency in the patient tested. Both Xtandi® and Zytiga® have a side effect profile similar to that of hormonal therapy. With patients for whom Xtandi® and Zytiga® are not effective or are unlikely to be effective as indicated by positive genetic markers (BRCA1 and BRCA2), we may prescribe Lynparza® (olaparib), which is known as a PARP inhibitor (poly ADP-ribose polymerase). Many patients fare quite well with Lynparza®. Another immunotherapy agent, Keytruda® (pembrolizumab) is known as a PD1 inhibitor. We are finding that patients who are not responding well to Lynparza may benefit from Keytruda. The Dattoli Cancer Center, has a growing arsenal of medications at our disposal for patients with advanced or recurrent disease. Both hormonal therapies and immunotherapies are associated with far less toxicity than chemotherapy as they are “targeted therapies” While genetic testing is important for the patient’s siblings and children, (and also for the patient on occasion), there is even greater importance in sampling the actual cancerous tissue removed from the patient in order to identify somatic mutations. This is known as comprehensive genomic profiling (CGP). This test can help identify exactly which treatment may benefit the patient (e.g. AR-7 mutations suggest resistance to Xtandi®/Zytiga® while HRR gene mutations predict response to Lynparza). Checkpoint inhibitors (e.g. PD-1) suggest sensitivity to pembrolizumab. We have been using FoundationOne ®CDx as the best genomic test currently available for identifying somatic mutations. This test searches 324 genes for cancer-relevant mutations in the DNA.
Industry Groups: Biotechnology, Health Care, Science and Engineering
